	<annotation>
		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						An vllus idem agere potuisset uel peritiùs; uel
						efficacius[que]
						vel deniq[ue] expeditiùs? Si hominum vllus, Tui te
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="vllus idem" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="agere potuisset" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						pudeat:
						et coge omnem artem, virtutemq[ue] absolutiùs.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nondu[m] es ille vir. Sed esse potes, si esse vis; et vis seriò.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Can anyone accomplish the same thing either more skillfully, more effectively, or even more quickly?
				If any man is ashamed of you, gather together completely every art and virtue .
				You are not yet that man. But you can become him, if you wish to be, and if you wish seriously.			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Jupiter merentibus offert.
						Sat agit, qui sat agit. Par est fortuna Labori.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Jupiter"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Jupiter gives to those who are worthy.
				He who acts enough, acts enough. Fortune is proper for work.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quin etiam Methodica, practicaq[ue] dexteritas infinitas supplet industrias.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Indeed, a methodical and practical skillfulness provides infinite industriousness.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EL">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						πολύτεχνος ἀνὴρ, πολλῶν ἀντάξιος ἄλλων.
						Οἱος πέπνυται, λοιποὶ σκιαι ἀισσουσι.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						ἀιὲν ἀριστεύειν, καὶ ὑπείροχον ἔμμεναι ἄλλων.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A poly-technic man, worth just as much as most other men.
				Αlone, he is prudent; the others move like shadows. <!-- CG: Unclear about this translation; I think this is Harvey writing Greek for himself and I'm not sure it's correct. --> <!--JG: I really can't help you with this. Will ask specialist-->
				Always to be the best and to be distinguished above the others.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Idem etiam Para[e]neticum Consilium Isocratis, et ipsius Salomonis,
						vt quisq[ue] contendat pra[e]cellere.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Isocrates"/>
					<person name="Solomon"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Likewise, even the encouraging advice of Isocrates and of Solomon himself, 
				as everyone strains to excel.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
